The main characteristics of cloud computing [3] are:

•Broad network access: This allows capabilities where resources can be accessed over the network using standard mechanisms which promote the use of thin and thick platforms such as laptops, tablets and mobile phones;
•Rapid elasticity: This allows CSPs to flexibly and rapidly cater services, thereby allowing these capabilities to be scaled both inwardly and outwardly, commensurately with the required demand;
•Measured service: Cloud resources use can be controlled, measured and reported.

 It differs from other models in that all the cloud resources are supplied and managed by the organisation only;
•Hybrid: This model is a combination of a private and public cloud where a private cloud is linked to one or more public cloud services; and
•Community: This model consists of a cloud infrastructure that is used exclusively by consumers who are part of a community of organisations with shared interests in concerns such as compliance issues and policy, security requirements and missions [10].

Cloud-computing systems are categorised into the following layers [14]:

•Applications: This layer allows end-users to access available cloud services through web portals for a fee or free of charge;
•Software infrastructure: This layer consists of fundamental resources that are used to construct new cloud applications and provide additional software environments for development in the cloud;
•Software kernel: This layer provides software management for cloud servers; and
•Hardware: This layer is at the bottom of the cloud stack and consists of the physical components of the cloud environment.

